WEBVTT

00:02.036 --> 00:05.671
A hoard of priceless treasures
lost beneath waves...

00:05.673 --> 00:09.207
HOFF: He was dead-set on reaping
a lot of gold from the lake,

00:09.209 --> 00:12.844
but Mother Nature
had other ideas.

00:12.846 --> 00:16.081
...the truth behind Moses
and the burning bush...

00:16.083 --> 00:18.984
MAROD: He set out
to find an explanation

00:18.986 --> 00:21.019
for the burning bush.

00:21.021 --> 00:24.756
...and one brave solider
faces down an entire army.

00:24.758 --> 00:27.493
NEVGLOSKI:
He was under constant fire
the entire time.

00:27.495 --> 00:31.263
He didn't stand a chance
against the attacking force.

00:31.265 --> 00:33.865
These are the
"Mysteries at the Museum."

00:33.867 --> 00:38.436
♪♪

00:38.438 --> 00:41.239
The Elizabeth River
twists and turns its way

00:41.241 --> 00:44.175
through the southern city
of Portsmouth, Virginia,

00:44.177 --> 00:46.645
and moored along
this winding waterway

00:46.647 --> 00:51.049
is an historic battleship --
the USS Wisconsin.

00:51.051 --> 00:55.554
The 887-foot-long vessel
saw action during World War II,

00:55.556 --> 00:56.721
the Korean War,

00:56.723 --> 01:00.392
and was even used
in Operation Desert Storm.

01:00.394 --> 01:02.293
But on the other side
of the river

01:02.295 --> 01:04.462
is a very different landmark --

01:04.464 --> 01:06.865
The Hill House Museum.

01:06.867 --> 01:10.202
♪♪

01:10.204 --> 01:13.538
Celebrating the life and times
of the eponymous Hill family,

01:13.540 --> 01:16.241
who lived here
for more than 130 years,

01:16.243 --> 01:20.745
the museum is home to
a host of antique heirlooms.

01:20.747 --> 01:25.917
Among them is china once used
by First Lady Dolley Madison,

01:25.919 --> 01:29.521
a hand-painted 1920s
porcelain doll,

01:29.523 --> 01:31.924
and a glass urn
that was given as a prize

01:31.926 --> 01:35.093
at the 1943
International Flower Show.

01:35.095 --> 01:37.896
♪♪

01:37.898 --> 01:40.164
But among these
decorative artifacts

01:40.166 --> 01:43.167
is one that is
purely functional.

01:43.169 --> 01:45.270
WEATHERFORD:
It is made of white porcelain.

01:45.272 --> 01:47.506
There is a stainless-steel
center

01:47.508 --> 01:49.908
connected to a rubber hose.

01:49.910 --> 01:53.378
The artifact is 2 feet
by about 15 inches deep

01:53.380 --> 01:57.583
and has a reflective metal lid
that covers objects inside.

01:59.953 --> 02:03.088
WILDMAN: The origins
of this ingenious device

02:03.090 --> 02:05.624
are linked to
an unexpected inventor

02:05.626 --> 02:08.593
and a bizarre twist of fate.

02:08.595 --> 02:13.264
This dishwasher spins a tale
of soap, suds, and sacrifice.

02:13.266 --> 02:16.668
♪♪

02:16.670 --> 02:20.973
WILDMAN: It's the early 1880s
in Shelbyville, Illinois.

02:20.975 --> 02:23.408
William Cochrane is
a prosperous merchant

02:23.410 --> 02:25.610
and a Democratic politician.

02:25.612 --> 02:28.480
He and his wife, Josephine,
sit at the very heart

02:28.482 --> 02:31.449
of the city's
thriving social scene.

02:31.451 --> 02:32.884
WEATHERFORD:
Josephine and William Cochrane

02:32.886 --> 02:35.087
enjoyed a very comfortable
life together.

02:35.089 --> 02:37.422
William was a prosperous
business owner,

02:37.424 --> 02:39.625
and Josephine was seen
as a socialite.

02:39.627 --> 02:41.026
The couple was very well-known

02:41.028 --> 02:42.995
for throwing
extravagant parties.

02:44.698 --> 02:48.233
WILDMAN: But there is more to
Josephine than meets the eye.

02:48.235 --> 02:51.102
Josephine, in some ways,
was a typical woman

02:51.104 --> 02:53.071
of her station in that time,

02:53.073 --> 02:56.574
but in a lot of ways
was pretty unique.

02:56.576 --> 02:59.077
WILDMAN: The society hostess
comes from a long line

02:59.079 --> 03:01.413
of inventors and engineers.

03:01.415 --> 03:04.916
WEATHERFORD:
Her great-grandfather held
a patent for a steamship.

03:04.918 --> 03:07.185
She really did come from people
who were very industrious

03:07.187 --> 03:08.720
and very creative.

03:08.722 --> 03:11.223
WILDMAN:
And Josephine is no exception.

03:11.225 --> 03:14.425
She enjoyed tinkering around
with different inventions,

03:14.427 --> 03:15.793
and that was kind of
a hobby of hers

03:15.795 --> 03:18.030
and very unusual at that time.

03:20.534 --> 03:23.435
WILDMAN:
Now Josephine has turned
her inquisitive instincts

03:23.437 --> 03:26.938
to solving a pesky
domestic problem.

03:26.940 --> 03:29.474
WEATHERFORD:
She realized that their heirloom
china was being damaged

03:29.476 --> 03:32.544
by servants being careless
about washing it.

03:32.546 --> 03:36.881
Her china was very precious,
that dated back to the 1600s.

03:36.883 --> 03:39.418
WILDMAN:
To prevent her prized plates
from being damaged

03:39.420 --> 03:41.052
by the careless servants,

03:41.054 --> 03:44.823
Josephine takes on the task
of washing the dishes herself.

03:46.126 --> 03:47.826
WEATHERFORD:
Josephine decided at that moment

03:47.828 --> 03:49.227
that the servants
would no longer

03:49.229 --> 03:50.662
wash the dishes after the party,

03:50.664 --> 03:55.200
and only she could be trusted
to wash these heirloom dishes.

03:55.202 --> 03:57.502
This was hours and hours
of work.

03:57.504 --> 03:58.837
I don't think she quite knew

03:58.839 --> 04:00.805
what she was
getting herself into.

04:00.807 --> 04:03.709
WILDMAN:
One day, while elbow-deep
in soapy water,

04:03.711 --> 04:05.677
she has a revelation.

04:05.679 --> 04:07.713
WEATHERFORD: As she was washing
these countless dishes,

04:07.715 --> 04:10.315
Josephine had the idea
that there needed to be

04:10.317 --> 04:12.851
a dishwashing machine.

04:12.853 --> 04:15.854
WILDMAN:
And who better to design
and build such a device

04:15.856 --> 04:18.123
than Josephine herself?

04:18.125 --> 04:20.458
Even though she didn't have
any formal training

04:20.460 --> 04:24.629
as a mechanic or an engineer,
she wound up with a machine

04:24.631 --> 04:26.865
that would rinse
several dishes at one time

04:26.867 --> 04:28.867
with a hand-crank operation.

04:28.869 --> 04:31.136
WILDMAN: But before she can
finish the job,

04:31.138 --> 04:33.972
fate deals her a crushing blow.

04:33.974 --> 04:38.877
In 1883, her husband,
William Cochrane, dies.

04:38.879 --> 04:42.748
Josephine is devastated
by the loss of her true love.

04:42.750 --> 04:45.116
WEATHERFORD: Her entire life
was completely derailed

04:45.118 --> 04:47.618
when her husband died
very unexpectedly,

04:47.620 --> 04:51.489
and for a woman
of her station in her time,

04:51.491 --> 04:54.760
this left her
completely and utterly alone.

04:54.762 --> 04:57.028
WILDMAN:
But that's not the worst of it.

04:57.030 --> 04:59.297
The widow soon learns
that her husband

04:59.299 --> 05:01.900
had harbored a terrible secret.

05:01.902 --> 05:03.835
WEATHERFORD:
She had always thought
they were very stable

05:03.837 --> 05:05.871
and very comfortable
financially,

05:05.873 --> 05:09.040
and she found out that he
had been completely careless.

05:09.042 --> 05:11.109
He had squandered
all of their money,

05:11.111 --> 05:14.279
and she was deeply in debt.

05:14.281 --> 05:17.516
WILDMAN: Josephine is forced to
settle her husband's debts

05:17.518 --> 05:19.151
any way she can.

05:19.153 --> 05:20.418
WEATHERFORD:
Her clothes were taken away.

05:20.420 --> 05:22.287
Even her dishes were taken away.

05:22.289 --> 05:24.322
Everything had to be repossessed

05:24.324 --> 05:26.658
in order to help pay down
these debts.

05:26.660 --> 05:28.559
WILDMAN:
Faced with financial ruin,

05:28.561 --> 05:30.128
Josephine turns her thoughts

05:30.130 --> 05:33.531
back to her yet-unfinished
mechanical dishwasher.

05:33.533 --> 05:36.168
♪♪

05:36.170 --> 05:38.003
For months, she labors away,

05:38.005 --> 05:41.673
finessing the details
of the design.

05:41.675 --> 05:44.142
Finally, she strikes upon
the secret

05:44.144 --> 05:47.178
to making the device a success.

05:47.180 --> 05:49.948
WEATHERFORD:
She realized she needed
pressurized water,

05:49.950 --> 05:53.651
and that was what would actually
help effectively clean dishes.

05:54.755 --> 05:59.390
WILDMAN:
Josephine adds a spinning cage,
driven by a hand-powered rotor,

05:59.392 --> 06:02.361
and a hose that will blast
the dishes with hot water.

06:03.463 --> 06:05.297
WEATHERFORD:
The hand crank would
spin the dishes around,

06:05.299 --> 06:08.300
enabling the water to swish
through and clean them.

06:08.302 --> 06:11.435
WILDMAN: To test the machine,
she fills it with dishes

06:11.437 --> 06:13.538
and starts it up.

06:13.540 --> 06:16.842
At the end of the cycle,
she lifts the lid.

06:16.844 --> 06:19.911
The dishes are sparkling clean.

06:19.913 --> 06:22.547
It used pressurized jets
that sprayed soapy water

06:22.549 --> 06:24.449
from above the dishes
and below them,

06:24.451 --> 06:26.418
which effectively cleaned them.

06:28.856 --> 06:31.523
WILDMAN:
On December 28th, 1886,

06:31.525 --> 06:33.792
Josephine Cochrane
receives a patent

06:33.794 --> 06:35.994
for her mechanical dishwasher.

06:35.996 --> 06:38.429
Her invention is a huge hit.

06:38.431 --> 06:41.233
In the years that follow,
she launches her own company

06:41.235 --> 06:44.469
and goes on to become
wealthy in her own right.

06:44.471 --> 06:46.871
Her company ended up going
through several transitions,

06:46.873 --> 06:49.708
but today we would know this
as the Whirlpool company.

06:52.078 --> 06:55.747
WILDMAN:
By the 1950s, the automatic
dishwasher is a staple

06:55.749 --> 06:57.682
in homes across the country...

06:57.684 --> 07:02.320
ANNOUNCER:
This new dishwasher can do
dishes faster, cleaner, better

07:02.322 --> 07:04.488
than any other way.

07:04.490 --> 07:07.859
Just look at those
gleaming dishes.

07:07.861 --> 07:10.695
WILDMAN: ...and it's all thanks
to the innovative instincts

07:10.697 --> 07:13.064
of a cash-strapped widow.

07:13.066 --> 07:16.434
Today, this early 20th century
electric dishwasher

07:16.436 --> 07:18.770
is on display
at the Hill House Museum

07:18.772 --> 07:20.338
in Portsmouth, Virginia.

07:20.340 --> 07:23.575
It recalls the wily woman
whose clever invention

07:23.577 --> 07:25.710
made kitchen cleanup a whiz.

07:25.712 --> 07:29.047
♪♪

07:29.049 --> 07:30.915
At the base of
the Rocky Mountains

07:30.917 --> 07:34.452
is the mile-high city
of Denver, Colorado.

07:34.454 --> 07:38.723
Residents and visitors alike
can enjoy an atmospheric perk.

07:38.725 --> 07:41.993
Golf balls hit here
will travel 10% farther

07:41.995 --> 07:43.461
than at sea level,

07:43.463 --> 07:46.231
but in the center of the city
sits an institution

07:46.233 --> 07:49.567
celebrating not altitude
but artistry --

07:49.569 --> 07:51.503
the Denver Art Museum.

07:51.505 --> 07:56.308
♪♪

07:56.310 --> 07:58.009
Culture-loving travelers
can find

07:58.011 --> 08:01.146
an inlaid wooden tray
from Chile,

08:01.148 --> 08:03.181
an earthenware plate
from Guatemala

08:03.183 --> 08:05.716
dating back to 600 A.D.

08:05.718 --> 08:08.753
and a 1,000-year-old
Costa Rican grinding stone

08:08.755 --> 08:10.621
carved in the shape of a jaguar.

08:10.623 --> 08:14.492
♪♪

08:14.494 --> 08:19.330
But among these ancient wares is
one singularly standout piece.

08:19.332 --> 08:20.765
HOFF:
The object is circular

08:20.767 --> 08:23.368
and about five inches
in diameter.

08:23.370 --> 08:26.571
It is golden in color
and sparkles in the light.

08:26.573 --> 08:27.906
It has been embossed
with the image of

08:27.908 --> 08:30.942
a supernatural being
from an ancient civilization.

08:33.213 --> 08:35.747
WILDMAN: This wondrous treasure
and those like it

08:35.749 --> 08:37.515
tell of an extraordinary quest

08:37.517 --> 08:40.452
for untold riches
just out of reach.

08:41.521 --> 08:43.855
HOFF: This is a story
about gold, greed,

08:43.857 --> 08:45.557
and the power of nature.

08:45.559 --> 08:51.696
♪♪

08:51.698 --> 08:53.598
WILDMAN:
Ever since the 1500s,

08:53.600 --> 08:56.401
when the Spanish conquistadors
first made contact

08:56.403 --> 08:59.637
with the people of
Central and South America,

08:59.639 --> 09:02.807
stories have abounded
of shimmering temples,

09:02.809 --> 09:07.078
overflowing mines,
and cities paved with gold.

09:07.080 --> 09:10.882
The Spanish were absolutely
crazy for these precious metals.

09:10.884 --> 09:14.819
♪♪

09:14.821 --> 09:17.922
WILDMAN: One legend above all
stands apart.

09:17.924 --> 09:21.226
It concerns the Muisca people,
who, for 1,000 years,

09:21.228 --> 09:23.828
lived on the shores
of Lake Guatavita

09:23.830 --> 09:26.030
in what is now Colombia.

09:26.032 --> 09:28.366
HOFF: The Muisca spirituality
encompassed many elements

09:28.368 --> 09:29.500
of the natural world,

09:29.502 --> 09:32.303
such as the sun,
the moon, and water.

09:32.305 --> 09:33.637
WILDMAN:
And according to the story,

09:33.639 --> 09:35.507
they honored
these elemental gods

09:35.509 --> 09:37.909
with an extraordinary ritual.

09:37.911 --> 09:40.177
Each time a new chieftain
was named,

09:40.179 --> 09:42.447
he would be adorned in gold dust

09:42.449 --> 09:44.649
and rowed to
the middle of the lake.

09:44.651 --> 09:48.853
There, he would submerge himself
in the emerald-green waters.

09:48.855 --> 09:51.156
HOFF: All the gold dust
would wash off of him

09:51.158 --> 09:53.058
while other important people
in the group

09:53.060 --> 09:54.793
threw offerings into the lake

09:54.795 --> 09:58.196
that included other gold pieces
and precious stones.

09:58.198 --> 10:01.933
The gold would then sink
to the bottom of the lake.

10:01.935 --> 10:05.136
WILDMAN:
For the Spanish, the story
of these sunken treasures --

10:05.138 --> 10:07.872
ones similar to this breastplate
now on display

10:07.874 --> 10:10.107
at the Denver Art Museum
in Colorado --

10:10.109 --> 10:12.177
proved irresistible.

10:12.179 --> 10:16.581
In 1545, a man named
Hernán Pérez de Quesada

10:16.583 --> 10:20.018
set out to retrieve the gold
at the bottom of the lake.

10:20.020 --> 10:23.088
HOFF: He was second in command
in his older brother's army,

10:23.090 --> 10:25.623
and it was his job to go explore

10:25.625 --> 10:28.526
the unexplored-by-European
highlands

10:28.528 --> 10:30.595
in what is now Colombia.

10:30.597 --> 10:33.498
WILDMAN: And he adopted
an unconventional strategy.

10:33.500 --> 10:35.433
HOFF:
He decided that the best way

10:35.435 --> 10:38.069
was to try to
lower the lake level by hand.

10:39.806 --> 10:42.673
WILDMAN:
He ordered his men to pull
bucket after bucket

10:42.675 --> 10:44.275
of water from the lake.

10:44.277 --> 10:47.045
HOFF:
After months of grueling work
in the dry season,

10:47.047 --> 10:49.514
the men had only managed
to lower the lake level

10:49.516 --> 10:51.416
by about 10 feet.

10:51.418 --> 10:54.652
WILDMAN:
The treasure hunters did find
a few trinkets along the shore,

10:54.654 --> 10:56.488
but when the lake level
rose again,

10:56.490 --> 10:58.923
de Quesada
abandoned the project.

10:58.925 --> 11:01.726
♪♪

11:01.728 --> 11:02.994
Forty years later,

11:02.996 --> 11:05.329
a rich merchant
named Antonio de Sepúlveda

11:05.331 --> 11:08.600
made another attempt
to find the treasures.

11:08.602 --> 11:11.135
He instructed workers
to cut a large notch

11:11.137 --> 11:14.805
in the rim of the lake
to allow the water to flow out.

11:14.807 --> 11:18.342
He actually managed to lower
the lake level by about 65 feet,

11:18.344 --> 11:22.047
and you can still see
a notch cut in the side today.

11:22.049 --> 11:24.882
WILDMAN: It's said that he found
golden breastplates,

11:24.884 --> 11:29.587
a golden staff, and an emerald
the size of a hen's egg.

11:29.589 --> 11:31.556
All of this went pretty much
straight back

11:31.558 --> 11:33.091
to the king of Spain.

11:33.093 --> 11:35.693
WILDMAN: But once again,
the project was cut short.

11:37.097 --> 11:40.832
HOFF:
Part of the notch collapsed,
killing most of the workforce,

11:40.834 --> 11:43.634
and the merchant
abandoned his plan.

11:43.636 --> 11:47.305
WILDMAN: For the next 300 years,
people searched in vain

11:47.307 --> 11:49.641
for the sunken gold
of the Muisca.

11:52.078 --> 11:54.913
Then, in the beginning
of the 20th century,

11:54.915 --> 11:58.383
a British engineer comes along
who is determined to finally

11:58.385 --> 12:02.720
collect the vast treasure
at the bottom of Lake Guatavita.

12:02.722 --> 12:05.589
His name is Hartley Knowles.

12:05.591 --> 12:08.059
HOFF:
Hartley Knowles had heard about
the gold in Lake Guatavita

12:08.061 --> 12:10.060
and decided that
his mechanical skills

12:10.062 --> 12:13.731
made him the perfect person
to go after those treasures.

12:13.733 --> 12:16.267
WILDMAN:
Knowles' idea is to dig a tunnel

12:16.269 --> 12:19.837
nearly 1/4 mile long
under the lake.

12:19.839 --> 12:22.073
Then, he will use a steam pump

12:22.075 --> 12:24.142
and a system
of sluices and screens

12:24.144 --> 12:25.943
to direct the lake water away,

12:25.945 --> 12:29.080
while retaining any
solid objects left behind.

12:29.082 --> 12:32.717
It was a crazy plan, but Knowles
was convinced it would work.

12:34.821 --> 12:39.457
WILDMAN:
But the eager engineer has no
idea what surprises lie ahead.

12:39.459 --> 12:41.960
Knowles was dead-set
on reaping his rewards,

12:41.962 --> 12:44.696
but Mother Nature
had other ideas.

12:44.698 --> 12:48.066
♪♪

12:51.905 --> 12:54.305
It's the early 1900s.

12:54.307 --> 12:57.642
A British engineer named
Hartley Knowles is on a mission

12:57.644 --> 13:01.412
to dredge up a hoard
of priceless ancient artifacts

13:01.414 --> 13:04.782
from the bottom of a lake
in Colombia, South America.

13:04.784 --> 13:08.920
So, can Knowles dig deep and
recover these long-lost wonders?

13:10.790 --> 13:13.258
For more than a decade,
Knowles and his crew

13:13.260 --> 13:15.726
worked their way
under the legendary lake.

13:15.728 --> 13:18.329
Gradually, they begin
to make progress.

13:18.331 --> 13:19.863
HOFF:
After several years of digging,

13:19.865 --> 13:23.368
water finally started
to drain away out of the lake.

13:23.370 --> 13:27.105
WILDMAN:
From the edges of the lake,
Knowles and his team recover

13:27.107 --> 13:30.508
spectacular Muisca ornaments
made of gold.

13:30.510 --> 13:31.775
HOFF:
By Knowles' own estimate,

13:31.777 --> 13:34.411
the objects were worth
about $20,000.

13:34.413 --> 13:37.715
That's about half a million
dollars in today's money.

13:37.717 --> 13:40.685
This must have been a very
exciting moment for Knowles.

13:40.687 --> 13:43.387
♪♪

13:43.389 --> 13:45.957
WILDMAN:
But they are convinced that
the lion's share remains

13:45.959 --> 13:47.959
embedded in the soft silt

13:47.961 --> 13:50.228
that sits in the middle
of the lake bed,

13:50.230 --> 13:52.997
and that's a problem
for Knowles and his men.

13:52.999 --> 13:56.900
HOFF:
The middle of the lake was still
covered in mud and slime.

13:56.902 --> 13:58.736
It was almost impenetrable.

13:58.738 --> 14:01.973
WILDMAN: Before they can come up
with a plan to extract the gold,

14:01.975 --> 14:04.308
things take a turn
for the worse.

14:04.310 --> 14:07.846
HOFF: The sun baked the lake bed
to the consistency of cement.

14:07.848 --> 14:09.781
It was impossible
to break through.

14:12.051 --> 14:15.987
WILDMAN: Knowles is forced to
abandon the project.

14:15.989 --> 14:19.123
HOFF:
The exact value of what remains
in the lake is unknown,

14:19.125 --> 14:22.960
but presumably there's still
a lot of gold in there.

14:22.962 --> 14:26.330
WILDMAN:
And whatever remains now
may never be recovered.

14:26.332 --> 14:30.067
In 1965, the Colombian
government put Lake Guatavita

14:30.069 --> 14:31.402
under legal protection

14:31.404 --> 14:33.070
as part of the nation's
historical

14:33.072 --> 14:34.738
and cultural heritage.

14:34.740 --> 14:38.042
♪♪

14:38.044 --> 14:40.144
Today, this
golden breastplate --

14:40.146 --> 14:43.114
similar to artifacts
thrown into Lake Guatavita

14:43.116 --> 14:44.715
more than five centuries ago --

14:44.717 --> 14:48.219
is on display at the
Denver Art Museum in Colorado.

14:48.221 --> 14:50.421
It serves as a reminder
of a treasure

14:50.423 --> 14:52.824
that may be just beyond reach.

14:52.826 --> 14:56.494
♪♪

14:56.496 --> 14:58.496
Washington, DC.

14:58.498 --> 15:00.765
One of the most solemn
and sacred places

15:00.767 --> 15:02.133
in the nation's capital

15:02.135 --> 15:04.835
is the Vietnam War Memorial.

15:04.837 --> 15:08.406
Dedicated in 1982,
this awe-inspiring tribute

15:08.408 --> 15:09.807
is engraved with the names

15:09.809 --> 15:13.444
of more than 58,000
U.S. servicemen and women

15:13.446 --> 15:17.281
who gave their lives
in the Vietnam conflict.

15:17.283 --> 15:18.649
And 30 miles south,

15:18.651 --> 15:20.918
in the small town
of Triangle, Virginia,

15:20.920 --> 15:22.520
is another memorial.

15:22.522 --> 15:24.488
It honors a branch
of the military

15:24.490 --> 15:27.891
whose members fought
in that war and many others --

15:27.893 --> 15:30.461
the National Museum
of the Marine Corps.

15:30.463 --> 15:34.798
♪♪

15:34.800 --> 15:36.867
The collection includes a baton

15:36.869 --> 15:39.370
presented to famed
Marine Corps band director

15:39.372 --> 15:42.206
and composer of
"Stars and Stripes Forever,"

15:42.208 --> 15:44.876
John Philip Sousa,

15:44.878 --> 15:48.212
an Oscar awarded for
a 1944 documentary

15:48.214 --> 15:51.316
produced by the Marines,

15:51.318 --> 15:52.683
and the American flag

15:52.685 --> 15:56.153
that was raised over
Iwo Jima in 1945.

15:56.155 --> 15:59.790
♪♪

15:59.792 --> 16:04.195
But among these iconic artifacts
is one that was used in battle.

16:05.398 --> 16:08.032
The artifact is very soft
to the touch,

16:08.034 --> 16:09.600
but also very durable.

16:09.602 --> 16:12.637
It is brown, green, beige
in color.

16:12.639 --> 16:14.205
It is meant to be worn

16:14.207 --> 16:16.507
but is also designed
to protect the wearer.

16:18.778 --> 16:22.446
WILDMAN: This uniform is linked
to a death-defying mission

16:22.448 --> 16:24.582
that saved countless lives.

16:24.584 --> 16:28.119
This is a story about a Marine,
a bridge, and an act of heroism.

16:28.121 --> 16:35.426
♪♪

16:35.428 --> 16:37.795
WILDMAN:
It's 1972.

16:37.797 --> 16:40.398
The Vietnam War has become
one of the most brutal

16:40.400 --> 16:43.400
and drawn-out conflicts
in history.

16:43.402 --> 16:46.336
North Vietnam aims to unify
the entire country

16:46.338 --> 16:48.606
under a single Communist regime.

16:48.608 --> 16:50.808
On the other hand,
the South Vietnamese government

16:50.810 --> 16:53.878
is fighting to preserve
a more democratic country.

16:55.981 --> 16:57.882
As the conflict winds down,

16:57.884 --> 17:01.552
the majority of U.S. personnel
have already been sent home.

17:01.554 --> 17:05.223
NEVGLOSKI:
The Vietnam War had been
going on for almost 30 years.

17:05.225 --> 17:09.226
By 1972, we had started
our drawdown.

17:09.228 --> 17:12.530
WILDMAN: However,
a small force remains behind.

17:12.532 --> 17:15.500
Their job is to assist
the South Vietnamese army

17:15.502 --> 17:18.970
in their continuing fight
against the Communist North.

17:18.972 --> 17:22.306
About 250 Marines were
still left in the country,

17:22.308 --> 17:24.776
acting as advisors
and assistance personnel.

17:27.046 --> 17:30.781
WILDMAN:
In March, the South Vietnamese
and U.S. forces get word

17:30.783 --> 17:33.918
that 20,000 Communist troops
are heading to capture

17:33.920 --> 17:37.021
the South Vietnamese capital
of Saigon.

17:37.023 --> 17:39.557
To get there,
they must cross a river

17:39.559 --> 17:44.061
by way of the 500-foot-long
Dong Ha Bridge.

17:44.063 --> 17:47.865
A battalion of just 600
South Vietnamese soldiers

17:47.867 --> 17:49.967
and a handful of U.S. Marines

17:49.969 --> 17:52.336
are all that defend
the crossing point.

17:52.338 --> 17:54.738
They didn't stand a chance
against the attacking

17:54.740 --> 17:56.274
North Vietnamese force.

17:56.276 --> 18:00.144
♪♪

18:00.146 --> 18:04.281
WILDMAN:
But one Marine is determined
to stop them in their tracks --

18:04.283 --> 18:07.384
32-year-old Captain John Ripley.

18:07.386 --> 18:09.219
NEVGLOSKI: Captain Ripley
was all-American.

18:09.221 --> 18:10.621
He believed in his mission.

18:10.623 --> 18:14.225
He was very, very dedicated
to the Marine Corps.

18:14.227 --> 18:17.562
♪♪

18:17.564 --> 18:20.631
WILDMAN:
Ripley knows that if the
Communists cross the bridge,

18:20.633 --> 18:23.734
they will have
a clear path to Saigon.

18:23.736 --> 18:26.571
There's only one way
to stop them --

18:26.573 --> 18:29.440
destroy the bridge.

18:29.442 --> 18:31.309
NEVGLOSKI:
To blow the bridge up,
it was going to take

18:31.311 --> 18:35.045
several hundred pounds of TNT
to get the job done.

18:35.047 --> 18:38.716
WILDMAN: Ripley will have to rig
the explosives single-handedly.

18:38.718 --> 18:40.318
NEVGLOSKI:
Without blowing up the bridge,

18:40.320 --> 18:43.787
the entire province could
potentially fall within hours.

18:43.789 --> 18:47.491
WILDMAN: So, can Captain Ripley
stop an advancing army?

18:47.493 --> 18:49.861
♪♪

18:53.399 --> 18:57.268
April 2nd, 1972 -- Vietnam.

18:57.270 --> 18:59.804
U.S. Marine Captain John Ripley

18:59.806 --> 19:03.073
is facing an almost
impossible task.

19:03.075 --> 19:06.643
Vastly outnumbered, he must
hold off a massive assault

19:06.645 --> 19:08.779
by the North Vietnamese.

19:08.781 --> 19:11.649
So can he do it?

19:11.651 --> 19:14.384
Ripley plots out how
he will rig the structure

19:14.386 --> 19:17.588
using 500 pounds
of explosives.

19:17.590 --> 19:20.457
The challenge that
Captain Ripley had before him

19:20.459 --> 19:22.793
was enormous.

19:22.795 --> 19:24.996
WILDMAN:
Then he and Major James Smock

19:24.998 --> 19:28.265
transport the explosives
to the base of the bridge.

19:28.267 --> 19:32.603
Then he swings monkey-bar-style
along the girders,

19:32.605 --> 19:35.739
rigging the bridge
for detonation.

19:35.741 --> 19:39.810
He continues this
grueling process for 100 feet.

19:39.812 --> 19:43.280
He was under constant fire
the entire time.

19:43.282 --> 19:47.552
WILDMAN:
Five times, Ripley returns
hand-over-hand to the river bank

19:47.554 --> 19:49.687
to retrieve more dynamite,

19:49.689 --> 19:53.124
which he secures in a diagonal
pattern beneath the bridge.

19:53.126 --> 19:58.062
This way, he can get both
the explosion to twist and snap

19:58.064 --> 20:01.065
the steel girders,
as well as lift the bridge up,

20:01.067 --> 20:04.635
causing that 100-foot section
to collapse.

20:04.637 --> 20:08.272
WILDMAN: On his final trip,
he sets a timer for 30 minutes

20:08.274 --> 20:10.274
before making his way
back to shore.

20:12.311 --> 20:14.111
Concerned the timer could fail,

20:14.113 --> 20:16.714
Ripley and Smock attempt
to trigger the detonation

20:16.716 --> 20:18.449
from a car battery...

20:20.552 --> 20:22.653
...but nothing happens.

20:22.655 --> 20:25.856
Now they must hope
the timer does its job.

20:25.858 --> 20:28.559
♪♪

20:28.561 --> 20:30.894
[ Explosion ]

20:30.896 --> 20:32.763
NEVGLOSKI:
The bridge exploded.

20:32.765 --> 20:34.932
Captain Ripley looked in the air

20:34.934 --> 20:37.501
and saw large chunks
of the bridge --

20:37.503 --> 20:40.504
wood and steel --
flying through the air.

20:40.506 --> 20:43.306
WILDMAN: His Herculean efforts
have worked.

20:43.308 --> 20:45.843
Though the war continues
for another three years,

20:45.845 --> 20:48.045
Ripley succeeds
in slowing the advance

20:48.047 --> 20:49.847
of the North Vietnamese army.

20:49.849 --> 20:51.715
NEVGLOSKI: What this did
was save the lives

20:51.717 --> 20:53.917
of countless
South Vietnamese soldiers

20:53.919 --> 20:56.587
and his fellow advisors.

20:56.589 --> 21:00.057
WILDMAN: Today, Captain Ripley's
Marine uniform is on display

21:00.059 --> 21:02.159
at the National Museum
of the Marine Corps

21:02.161 --> 21:04.795
in Triangle, Virginia.

21:04.797 --> 21:09.533
It recalls a fearless hero who
became a one-man fighting force.

21:09.535 --> 21:14.871
♪♪

21:14.873 --> 21:17.574
Stretching along
the southeast coast of Italy

21:17.576 --> 21:20.978
is a vast region
covered with olive trees.

21:20.980 --> 21:25.349
Some of these magnificent groves
are more than 1,000 years old,

21:25.351 --> 21:27.451
and together they produce
more olive oil

21:27.453 --> 21:30.421
than anywhere on
the Apennine Peninsula,

21:30.423 --> 21:33.758
and in the town of Lecce
is a unique institution

21:33.760 --> 21:36.794
that delves deep into
the area's rich history --

21:36.796 --> 21:38.329
the Faggiano Museum.

21:38.331 --> 21:40.965
♪♪

21:40.967 --> 21:43.300
The building is made up
of an intricate series

21:43.302 --> 21:44.968
of underground chambers,

21:44.970 --> 21:48.439
some of which are as old
as Italy itself,

21:48.441 --> 21:51.075
and on display in
one of these ancient rooms

21:51.077 --> 21:53.911
is an assortment of
antique items that offer a clue

21:53.913 --> 21:58.516
to the story behind this
strange set of structures.

21:58.518 --> 22:00.418
COX: Three of the objects
are circular in shape

22:00.420 --> 22:01.919
with holes in the middle.

22:01.921 --> 22:05.489
The objects range in size from
an inch to a few inches long.

22:05.491 --> 22:07.825
They are light tan and brown
in color.

22:07.827 --> 22:10.527
♪♪

22:10.529 --> 22:13.931
WILDMAN: These aged relics
tell the extraordinary tale

22:13.933 --> 22:18.135
of how this museum
came into existence.

22:18.137 --> 22:20.638
COX: The artifacts represent
one family's incredible

22:20.640 --> 22:23.307
and unexpected journey
of discovery.

22:23.309 --> 22:29.814
♪♪

22:29.816 --> 22:33.317
WILDMAN:
It's 2000 in Lecce, Italy.

22:33.319 --> 22:36.020
45-year-old chef
Luciano Faggiano

22:36.022 --> 22:39.689
dreams of owning
his own restaurant.

22:39.691 --> 22:43.427
Luciano was a very, very
entrepreneurial man.

22:43.429 --> 22:46.563
He wanted to strike out on his
own and have his own trattoria.

22:46.565 --> 22:48.298
WILDMAN:
After years of planning,

22:48.300 --> 22:51.101
he's finally ready to begin
renovating a building

22:51.103 --> 22:52.570
in the center of town.

22:52.572 --> 22:54.505
COX: It was in pretty
good shape already.

22:54.507 --> 22:56.373
It was in a great location,

22:56.375 --> 22:58.576
so it was pretty much
the perfect space.

23:00.346 --> 23:03.447
WILDMAN: But one day, he notices
that the floor is damp.

23:03.449 --> 23:06.717
Luciano thought that there was
probably a broken pipe

23:06.719 --> 23:08.852
somewhere underground.

23:08.854 --> 23:10.721
WILDMAN: So with the help
of his two sons,

23:10.723 --> 23:14.925
Luciano starts to dig, in hopes
of finding the problematic pipe.

23:14.927 --> 23:17.661
Luciano did not think this was
going to be a major project.

23:17.663 --> 23:20.063
He figured a few days, tops.

23:20.065 --> 23:21.765
WILDMAN:
But to his utter surprise,

23:21.767 --> 23:23.967
what he unearths
is not a leaky pipe,

23:23.969 --> 23:26.737
but something
altogether different.

23:26.739 --> 23:31.075
Beneath the floor is a series of
intricate interlocking stones.

23:31.077 --> 23:32.676
It seems to be another floor

23:32.678 --> 23:36.346
that has been laid
sometime in the past.

23:36.348 --> 23:38.816
Intrigued, they continue to dig.

23:38.818 --> 23:42.652
Luciano and his son
dug for days and days.

23:42.654 --> 23:44.822
WILDMAN:
And their perseverance pays off.

23:44.824 --> 23:47.291
Below the stones,
they unearth what appears to be

23:47.293 --> 23:49.493
some sort of ancient chamber.

23:49.495 --> 23:53.630
COX: Luciano knew that he had
uncovered some part of history,

23:53.632 --> 23:56.366
but he had no idea
exactly what it was.

23:56.368 --> 23:58.035
WILDMAN:
He and his sons keep digging

23:58.037 --> 24:01.005
and discover a series
of underground rooms.

24:02.542 --> 24:06.377
On the walls of one
are sinister red markings.

24:06.379 --> 24:10.247
Another contains a ring
covered with cryptic symbols,

24:10.249 --> 24:14.385
and in others, broken objects
litter the floors.

24:14.387 --> 24:17.721
Luciano had unearthed a whole
new world beneath his feet.

24:17.723 --> 24:20.891
♪♪

24:20.893 --> 24:23.860
WILDMAN: In every direction,
they find doorways

24:23.862 --> 24:27.264
leading to more secret tunnels
and hidden chambers.

24:27.266 --> 24:29.866
He really now wanted to get
to the bottom of it.

24:29.868 --> 24:33.069
WILDMAN: So who built this
mysterious labyrinth, and when?

24:33.071 --> 24:36.874
♪♪

24:40.847 --> 24:42.846
It's the year 2000.

24:42.848 --> 24:45.749
Fulfilling his dream of
opening his own restaurant,

24:45.751 --> 24:49.753
Italian chef Luciano Faggiano
is renovating a building,

24:49.755 --> 24:51.989
where he makes
an unexpected discovery.

24:51.991 --> 24:53.557
Beneath his ground floor

24:53.559 --> 24:56.192
is a vast warren
of underground chambers

24:56.194 --> 24:58.496
filled with ancient artifacts.

24:58.498 --> 25:01.432
So where will this
mysterious labyrinth lead?

25:03.536 --> 25:06.002
Luciano brings in
an archaeologist

25:06.004 --> 25:09.907
to help him understand
this captivating discovery.

25:09.909 --> 25:12.343
COX:
They found out that the chamber
that they had uncovered

25:12.345 --> 25:14.945
was actually used by
the Romans to store grain,

25:14.947 --> 25:17.548
and they found
another chamber --

25:17.550 --> 25:18.749
kind of a basement area --

25:18.751 --> 25:21.752
that was used
by Franciscan nuns.

25:23.322 --> 25:26.022
WILDMAN: The archaeologist
explains the strange ring

25:26.024 --> 25:29.126
is made up of
early Christian symbols,

25:29.128 --> 25:31.629
and the mysterious red painting
was created

25:31.631 --> 25:33.797
some 900 years earlier

25:33.799 --> 25:36.767
by a military order
called the Knights Templar.

25:36.769 --> 25:38.168
They really began to realize

25:38.170 --> 25:40.304
that they were
unearthing history.

25:40.306 --> 25:42.906
♪♪

25:42.908 --> 25:45.275
WILDMAN: They even uncover
a burial chamber

25:45.277 --> 25:48.178
they learn is from
the 5th century BC.

25:48.180 --> 25:50.981
COX:
As they went deeper and deeper,

25:50.983 --> 25:53.517
just this stuff
just kept bubbling up --

25:53.519 --> 25:54.952
all of this history.

25:54.954 --> 25:58.055
It went all the way back
to the 5th century BC,

25:58.057 --> 25:59.522
straight through
the Renaissance.

25:59.524 --> 26:00.991
It was just so much stuff.

26:00.993 --> 26:02.660
It was really incredible.

26:04.730 --> 26:08.532
WILDMAN: Eventually,
they dig down nearly 40 feet,

26:08.534 --> 26:13.336
exposing more than 5,000 relics
from different eras,

26:13.338 --> 26:15.806
all stacked neatly
on top of each other.

26:15.808 --> 26:17.641
When civilizations fell,

26:17.643 --> 26:20.610
they literally just built
right on top of it,

26:20.612 --> 26:22.679
so the relics stayed in place.

26:22.681 --> 26:24.081
They built something else.

26:24.083 --> 26:26.317
Those relics fell,
and they built something else,

26:26.319 --> 26:29.019
so it was almost like
a layer cake of history.

26:30.822 --> 26:32.456
WILDMAN:
The do-it-yourself project

26:32.458 --> 26:35.559
that was originally meant
to take a week at most

26:35.561 --> 26:37.361
turns into
an elaborate enterprise

26:37.363 --> 26:40.297
that lasts nearly a decade.

26:40.299 --> 26:42.499
COX: Luciano started out
by just wanting

26:42.501 --> 26:45.569
to find that busted pipe,
but in the process,

26:45.571 --> 26:49.006
he really became kind of
an amateur archaeologist.

26:49.008 --> 26:51.341
WILDMAN: Instead of opening
a restaurant on the site,

26:51.343 --> 26:53.978
Luciano preserves
the findings of the dig

26:53.980 --> 26:57.781
and turns the whole
building into a museum.

26:57.783 --> 26:59.849
As for his culinary ambitions,

26:59.851 --> 27:02.385
he opens a cafe
just down the road.

27:02.387 --> 27:05.688
With the Museum Faggiano,
it was really incredible for him

27:05.690 --> 27:08.458
to have this kind of
unexpected dream come true,

27:08.460 --> 27:11.327
but then also to see
his trattoria come to life,

27:11.329 --> 27:13.530
and even better, he didn't
have to lift a shovel.

27:13.532 --> 27:14.664
It was a win-win.

27:15.934 --> 27:19.569
WILDMAN: Today, visitors to the
Faggiano Museum in Lecce, Italy,

27:19.571 --> 27:22.039
can see the remnants
of the underground world

27:22.041 --> 27:25.843
uncovered by an unwitting chef
turned historian.

27:25.845 --> 27:28.412
They recall
the home-improvement project

27:28.414 --> 27:31.481
that opened up a window
into the past.

27:31.483 --> 27:34.885
♪♪

27:34.887 --> 27:37.554
The entrance to the city
of Worcester, Massachusetts,

27:37.556 --> 27:40.691
is guarded by a giant,
inflatable polar bear

27:40.693 --> 27:42.292
named Orson.

27:42.294 --> 27:46.162
First erected in 1902 to promote
a local beverage company,

27:46.164 --> 27:49.299
he's served as
the area's mascot ever since,

27:49.301 --> 27:52.102
and just a few miles
from this lovable landmark

27:52.104 --> 27:55.238
is one of the region's
most prominent institutions --

27:55.240 --> 27:57.708
the American
Antiquarian Society.

28:00.045 --> 28:04.081
This research library
contains periodicals,
pamphlets, and books

28:04.083 --> 28:07.150
dating back to
the nation's earliest days.

28:07.152 --> 28:10.120
Visitors to the collection
can find a political cartoon

28:10.122 --> 28:14.558
from 1804, depicting
Thomas Jefferson as a rooster,

28:14.560 --> 28:19.529
an 1833 lithograph
of Andrew Jackson
dressed as a king,

28:19.531 --> 28:23.166
and original poems handwritten
in the late 19th century

28:23.168 --> 28:24.935
by Emily Dickinson herself.

28:24.937 --> 28:27.971
♪♪

28:27.973 --> 28:30.206
But one object here celebrates

28:30.208 --> 28:33.010
a far less well-known
historical figure.

28:33.012 --> 28:35.979
ALGEO: The artifact measures
about 6 inches wide

28:35.981 --> 28:38.214
by 4 1/2 inches tall.

28:38.216 --> 28:40.150
It's made of paper.

28:40.152 --> 28:44.354
On its surface is the image of
a man and thin black borders.

28:44.356 --> 28:46.423
It also has two dates on it --

28:46.425 --> 28:48.892
February 22nd and March 4th.

28:51.097 --> 28:54.765
WILDMAN: This handbill recalls
the bizarre origins of a craze

28:54.767 --> 28:58.635
that swept the country
more than 150 years ago.

28:58.637 --> 29:02.072
ALGEO: This is a story about
a clever salesman, an epic trek,

29:02.074 --> 29:04.508
and a national
sporting phenomenon.

29:04.510 --> 29:10.380
♪♪

29:10.382 --> 29:14.684
WILDMAN: It's fall 1860
in Boston, Massachusetts.

29:14.686 --> 29:17.187
The next presidential election
is looming.

29:17.189 --> 29:19.723
It's a four-way race
between Abraham Lincoln

29:19.725 --> 29:21.457
and three other candidates.

29:21.459 --> 29:24.128
It's a very important
presidential election.

29:24.130 --> 29:26.630
It was, of course, right on
the eve of the Civil War.

29:28.534 --> 29:31.668
WILDMAN:
One young man who's closely
following the campaign

29:31.670 --> 29:34.671
is a 22-year-old
door-to-door book salesman

29:34.673 --> 29:37.474
named Edward Payson Weston.

29:37.476 --> 29:39.676
ALGEO:
Weston was very charismatic.

29:39.678 --> 29:41.211
He was very handsome.

29:41.213 --> 29:44.080
He had no shortage
of self-esteem.

29:44.082 --> 29:46.750
He was what you would call
a dandy at that time.

29:46.752 --> 29:49.386
♪♪

29:49.388 --> 29:51.121
WILDMAN:
One night, Weston is at dinner

29:51.123 --> 29:54.024
with a friend of his
named George Eddy

29:54.026 --> 29:56.794
when the discussion
takes a heated turn.

29:56.796 --> 29:59.763
Weston says he is certain
Lincoln will be defeated

29:59.765 --> 30:01.431
by one of the challengers.

30:01.433 --> 30:03.233
ALGEO: Weston told Eddy
that he believed Lincoln

30:03.235 --> 30:05.435
would lose the election,
and his friend Eddy said,

30:05.437 --> 30:08.071
"No, Lincoln's going to
win the election."

30:08.073 --> 30:09.673
WILDMAN:
As the argument escalates,

30:09.675 --> 30:12.575
the two men decide to settle
the matter with a bet,

30:12.577 --> 30:14.711
but this is no ordinary wager.

30:14.713 --> 30:17.314
The stakes are highly unusual.

30:17.316 --> 30:20.116
ALGEO:
The loser would have to walk
from Boston to Washington,

30:20.118 --> 30:22.853
which was nearly 500 miles.

30:22.855 --> 30:24.120
WILDMAN:
Not only that --

30:24.122 --> 30:26.456
they will have to do so
in the dead of winter

30:26.458 --> 30:28.659
in just over a week.

30:28.661 --> 30:32.963
They decided that the person who
walked had to do it in 10 days

30:32.965 --> 30:34.798
and had to arrive in time

30:34.800 --> 30:38.768
to witness the inauguration
of whoever was elected.

30:38.770 --> 30:40.737
WILDMAN:
It's an outrageous undertaking,

30:40.739 --> 30:43.773
but Weston is certain
of his political prediction.

30:43.775 --> 30:47.277
♪♪

30:47.279 --> 30:51.415
On November 7th, 1860, when
the election results come in,

30:51.417 --> 30:54.284
Weston gets the shock
of his lifetime.

30:54.286 --> 30:57.054
Lincoln is declared the winner.

30:57.056 --> 30:59.356
Weston has lost his bet.

30:59.358 --> 31:02.159
To keep his end of the bargain,
he must now walk

31:02.161 --> 31:05.862
from Boston, Massachusetts,
to Washington, DC.

31:05.864 --> 31:07.497
ALGEO: This would be
far beyond anything

31:07.499 --> 31:10.067
Weston had ever
attempted in his life.

31:12.070 --> 31:16.273
WILDMAN: Inauguration Day
is March 4th, 1861.

31:16.275 --> 31:20.844
The distance from Boston
to DC is 470 miles.

31:20.846 --> 31:22.712
To make it within
the 10-day limit,

31:22.714 --> 31:26.216
he'll have to walk
approximately 50 miles a day.

31:26.218 --> 31:27.784
ALGEO:
It took a lot of planning,

31:27.786 --> 31:31.021
and he prepared for the walk
very carefully.

31:32.791 --> 31:37.294
WILDMAN:
On February 22nd, 1861,
Weston sets off,

31:37.296 --> 31:39.930
but his progress is slow.

31:39.932 --> 31:41.664
ALGEO:
None of the roads were paved,

31:41.666 --> 31:44.968
so it was an unbelievably
challenging task.

31:44.970 --> 31:47.203
There had been a lot of snow
that winter,

31:47.205 --> 31:49.039
and so it was very difficult
conditions

31:49.041 --> 31:52.476
for anyone to be out walking
at that time.

31:54.880 --> 31:57.614
WILDMAN: Nevertheless,
Weston refuses to give up,

31:57.616 --> 31:58.882
walking day and night,

31:58.884 --> 32:01.951
stopping only occasionally
to eat and rest.

32:01.953 --> 32:05.088
He was very, very determined
to finish this.

32:05.090 --> 32:06.857
WILDMAN:
As he plods along,

32:06.859 --> 32:09.793
word of his
unbelievable journey spreads.

32:09.795 --> 32:11.762
As the walk went on,
more and more people

32:11.764 --> 32:13.629
came out to see him walk.

32:13.631 --> 32:15.065
It was a spectacle.

32:15.067 --> 32:17.133
The crowd was so large.

32:17.135 --> 32:20.904
WILDMAN: But on March 2nd,
eight days into his epic march,

32:20.906 --> 32:22.906
Weston makes a grave error.

32:24.209 --> 32:27.711
Just south of Philadelphia,
he comes upon a fork in the road

32:27.713 --> 32:29.646
and makes a fateful choice.

32:29.648 --> 32:31.381
ALGEO: The roads were
very poorly marked,

32:31.383 --> 32:33.316
and he went down the wrong road,

32:33.318 --> 32:35.452
and it cost him
about nine miles,

32:35.454 --> 32:38.288
and that really was
a bad setback for him.

32:38.290 --> 32:42.025
WILDMAN:
Miles off course, he's forced
to retrace his steps,

32:42.027 --> 32:44.193
but the error
has cost him dearly.

32:44.195 --> 32:47.264
♪♪

32:47.266 --> 32:50.266
When he arrives in
Washington, DC, on March 4th,

32:50.268 --> 32:52.602
he has missed
Lincoln's swearing-in

32:52.604 --> 32:54.471
by a mere five hours.

32:54.473 --> 32:58.675
Weston did reach Washington
on Inauguration Day,

32:58.677 --> 33:01.544
but he did not arrive in time.

33:01.546 --> 33:05.115
Technically,
Weston lost the bet.

33:05.117 --> 33:07.717
WILDMAN:
But the story doesn't end there.

33:07.719 --> 33:09.953
The tale of this unusual wager

33:09.955 --> 33:12.889
is about to change
Weston's life forever.

33:12.891 --> 33:16.593
Weston was about to walk
his way into the history books.

33:21.817 --> 33:24.384
It's March 1861.

33:24.386 --> 33:28.121
After losing a bet on calling
the presidential election,

33:28.123 --> 33:32.359
a 22-year-old salesman has had
to pay a strange penalty.

33:32.361 --> 33:35.762
He's had to walk 500 miles
from Boston, Massachusetts,

33:35.764 --> 33:37.263
to Washington, DC,

33:37.265 --> 33:40.266
and witness the inauguration
of Abraham Lincoln,

33:40.268 --> 33:41.334
and although he arrives

33:41.336 --> 33:44.404
five hours after
the ceremony has finished,

33:44.406 --> 33:47.274
it turns out his journey
has only just begun.

33:49.377 --> 33:51.711
Though Weston fell short
of his goal,

33:51.713 --> 33:55.882
his trek generated
a huge wave of publicity.

33:55.884 --> 33:57.717
ALGEO: It was a major
accomplishment

33:57.719 --> 34:00.387
and one that the press
and people recognized.

34:02.657 --> 34:06.125
WILDMAN: So the clever salesman
parlays his newfound fame

34:06.127 --> 34:07.828
into a lucrative venture.

34:07.830 --> 34:10.196
He tours arenas
and roller-skating rinks

34:10.198 --> 34:11.397
around the country,

34:11.399 --> 34:13.666
charging curious onlookers
to watch him

34:13.668 --> 34:16.703
walk hundreds of miles
around each venue.

34:16.705 --> 34:18.738
ALGEO:
Weston had become a celebrity,

34:18.740 --> 34:23.076
and so it was a huge occasion
when Weston came to town.

34:23.078 --> 34:27.614
People would pay 10 to 50 cents
just to watch Weston walk

34:27.616 --> 34:30.884
for hours in circles
in these roller-skating rinks.

34:32.621 --> 34:36.156
WILDMAN: Before long, other avid
ambulators step forward

34:36.158 --> 34:40.160
to challenge Weston
to long-distance walking races,

34:40.162 --> 34:43.063
and a popular new sport is born.

34:43.065 --> 34:45.632
It's called pedestrianism.

34:45.634 --> 34:48.001
ALGEO: An ordinary,
everyday activity

34:48.003 --> 34:51.237
became the most popular
spectator sport

34:51.239 --> 34:52.939
in the United States.

34:52.941 --> 34:55.375
♪♪

34:55.377 --> 34:56.843
WILDMAN:
Today, this handbill,

34:56.845 --> 34:58.578
which celebrates
Weston's journey

34:58.580 --> 35:01.248
from Boston
to Washington, DC,

35:01.250 --> 35:04.451
resides in the archives of the
American Antiquarian Society

35:04.453 --> 35:06.820
in Worcester, Massachusetts.

35:06.822 --> 35:09.422
It serves as a reminder
of a political wager

35:09.424 --> 35:11.925
that launched a national craze.

35:11.927 --> 35:16.329
♪♪

35:16.331 --> 35:18.064
Virginia's capital of Richmond

35:18.066 --> 35:20.867
is situated on the banks
of the James River.

35:20.869 --> 35:23.069
This is the only waterway
in America

35:23.071 --> 35:24.604
where kayakers and rafters

35:24.606 --> 35:28.374
can catch Class IV rapids
in the middle of a city.

35:28.376 --> 35:30.944
But not far from the shores
of the raging torrent

35:30.946 --> 35:33.313
sits a peaceful institution --

35:33.315 --> 35:35.281
the Virginia Museum
of Fine Arts.

35:35.283 --> 35:39.619
♪♪

35:39.621 --> 35:41.754
Here, inquisitive visitors
can find

35:41.756 --> 35:44.890
ceremonial masks
from Burkina Faso,

35:44.892 --> 35:48.128
a statue of Julius Caesar
from the 1st century

35:48.130 --> 35:50.297
and five Fabergé eggs --

35:50.299 --> 35:52.966
the largest public collection
of the famed works

35:52.968 --> 35:54.301
in the United States.

35:56.605 --> 35:59.472
But among these iconic
cultural treasures

35:59.474 --> 36:02.776
is one item that's linked
to an incendiary tale.

36:03.745 --> 36:07.147
MAROD: The artifact is about
12 feet by 9 feet.

36:07.149 --> 36:10.083
It is woven
and made of many colors.

36:10.085 --> 36:12.952
It is over 500 years old

36:12.954 --> 36:15.055
and is meant to hang on a wall.

36:17.525 --> 36:21.661
WILDMAN:
This tapestry recalls a crusade
to uncover the truth

36:21.663 --> 36:24.998
behind a legend of
biblical proportions.

36:25.000 --> 36:27.166
This item tells the story
of a miracle

36:27.168 --> 36:29.869
and a scientific quest
for discovery.

36:29.871 --> 36:34.574
♪♪

36:34.576 --> 36:38.011
WILDMAN:
For millennia, the stories
of the Bible have mystified

36:38.013 --> 36:41.514
and fascinated historians
and scholars alike.

36:41.516 --> 36:44.684
Many have sought to find
a scientific explanation

36:44.686 --> 36:46.152
for the extraordinary events

36:46.154 --> 36:48.821
recounted in
these ancient texts.

36:48.823 --> 36:50.991
Some scholars would want
to prove that there is

36:50.993 --> 36:56.062
a scientific explanation
for these miracles.

36:56.064 --> 36:58.031
WILDMAN: For example,
could the destruction

36:58.033 --> 37:01.368
of the walls of Jericho
described in the Book of Joshua

37:01.370 --> 37:04.971
actually have been brought
down by an earthquake?

37:04.973 --> 37:06.773
And was the Star of Bethlehem

37:06.775 --> 37:10.510
that led the magi to Jesus
really a comet?

37:10.512 --> 37:11.978
♪♪

37:11.980 --> 37:15.848
But one particular
biblical tale stands apart --

37:15.850 --> 37:18.184
the story of the burning bush.

37:18.186 --> 37:21.020
♪♪

37:21.022 --> 37:22.922
According to the Book of Exodus,

37:22.924 --> 37:25.191
Moses was looking
after his flock

37:25.193 --> 37:28.061
when he noticed
something astonishing.

37:28.063 --> 37:30.196
While he was tending
to these sheep,

37:30.198 --> 37:32.865
he ended up on a mountain,

37:32.867 --> 37:36.936
where he saw a bush
all in flames.

37:36.938 --> 37:39.472
WILDMAN: But strangely,
although the fire raged,

37:39.474 --> 37:42.108
the bush was not consumed
by the flames.

37:43.478 --> 37:47.013
MAROD: Not only that, but
the voice of God spoke to him,

37:47.015 --> 37:49.416
saying that he had been chosen

37:49.418 --> 37:54.120
to lead
the Hebrews out of Egypt.

37:54.122 --> 37:57.590
♪♪

37:57.592 --> 38:00.526
WILDMAN: It's a pivotal moment
in religious history

38:00.528 --> 38:02.562
and appears in the sacred texts

38:02.564 --> 38:05.631
of Judaism,
Christianity, and Islam.

38:05.633 --> 38:08.368
It's also a source
of much debate.

38:08.370 --> 38:10.569
In 1995, one man --

38:10.571 --> 38:12.839
a fellow at
the Royal Academy of Engineering

38:12.841 --> 38:15.809
and a professor of
material science at Cambridge --

38:15.811 --> 38:19.512
decides to settle the issue
once and for all.

38:19.514 --> 38:22.115
His name is Colin Humphreys.

38:22.117 --> 38:26.186
Colin Humphreys was a scientist
and a devout Christian,

38:26.188 --> 38:28.988
and he felt<i> really</i>
passionately about combining

38:28.990 --> 38:31.524
both religion and science
together.

38:31.526 --> 38:34.060
♪♪

38:34.062 --> 38:37.430
WILDMAN:
Humphreys believes the answer
may lie on the very mountain

38:37.432 --> 38:40.266
where Moses was said
to have been tending his sheep.

38:40.268 --> 38:43.803
For many years, it was
thought to be Mount Sinai.

38:43.805 --> 38:46.739
MAROD: It was widely supposed
that this incident

38:46.741 --> 38:50.777
of Moses coming up to the
burning bush happened in Egypt.

38:50.779 --> 38:52.812
WILDMAN:
But Humphreys isn't so sure.

38:52.814 --> 38:54.948
He spends years
pondering the subject,

38:54.950 --> 38:57.250
but all his theories
lead nowhere...

38:59.688 --> 39:03.823
...and in 2002, while on a trip
to Mount Etna in Sicily,

39:03.825 --> 39:05.825
he has a revelation of his own.

39:05.827 --> 39:08.961
MAROD:
He had this "Aha!" moment
where he said,

39:08.963 --> 39:11.030
"This could explain
the burning bush."

39:11.032 --> 39:14.901
♪♪

39:18.490 --> 39:22.225
Of all the stories in the Bible,
one of the most mysterious

39:22.227 --> 39:25.060
is the tale of Moses
and the burning bush.

39:25.062 --> 39:27.697
For centuries,
scholars and historians

39:27.699 --> 39:30.199
have puzzled over
this extraordinary event.

39:30.201 --> 39:34.069
Did it really happen,
and if so, where and how?

39:34.071 --> 39:36.372
Now a professor named
Colin Humphreys

39:36.374 --> 39:38.274
thinks he may have found
the answer.

39:39.611 --> 39:43.213
As Humphreys climbs the volcano,
he notices hot gases

39:43.215 --> 39:45.248
escaping through vents
in the ground,

39:45.250 --> 39:48.218
so he conducts
an impromptu experiment.

39:48.220 --> 39:51.588
He dropped a piece of paper
into one of these holes,

39:51.590 --> 39:54.357
and it immediately
caught on fire.

39:54.359 --> 39:57.426
WILDMAN:
Humphreys suddenly realizes
that the biblical site

39:57.428 --> 40:01.798
where Moses stood was perhaps
no ordinary mountain.

40:01.800 --> 40:03.833
It may have been a volcano.

40:04.936 --> 40:07.336
MAROD:
According to Exodus,

40:07.338 --> 40:10.272
the mountain where Moses found
this burning bush

40:10.274 --> 40:12.141
was also shaking.

40:12.143 --> 40:15.145
It was covered in
fire and smoke.

40:15.147 --> 40:17.347
WILDMAN:
But something doesn't add up.

40:17.349 --> 40:20.349
Egypt's Mount Sinai
is not volcanic,

40:20.351 --> 40:21.818
and that's not all.

40:21.820 --> 40:25.288
MAROD: The problem was there
were no volcanos in Egypt

40:25.290 --> 40:27.156
that would have worked
with this theory.

40:27.158 --> 40:29.893
WILDMAN:
So Humphreys refines his theory.

40:29.895 --> 40:31.894
Could the epic event
have happened

40:31.896 --> 40:33.930
on a different mountain
altogether?

40:33.932 --> 40:35.965
Further east, in Saudi Arabia,

40:35.967 --> 40:39.636
Humphreys finds a volcano
named Mount Bedr.

40:41.372 --> 40:44.374
Not only that --
Saudi Arabia is also home

40:44.376 --> 40:46.910
to a plant named the acacia,

40:46.912 --> 40:51.313
which has a quality that matches
that of the famed burning bush.

40:51.315 --> 40:53.316
Acacia plants
can actually burn

40:53.318 --> 40:56.252
for very, very, very
long periods.

40:56.254 --> 40:58.487
WILDMAN: With all these factors
put together,

40:58.489 --> 41:02.024
the professor is convinced
he has the answer.

41:02.026 --> 41:04.194
MAROD: Humphreys concluded
that the burning bush

41:04.196 --> 41:08.331
was caused by very hot volcanic
gas emitting from the ground,

41:08.333 --> 41:10.800
and this bush was growing

41:10.802 --> 41:13.068
right on top of one
of these volcanic vents.

41:13.070 --> 41:17.006
♪♪

41:17.008 --> 41:18.474
WILDMAN:
Though unproven,

41:18.476 --> 41:21.210
Humphreys' theory remains
an intriguing addition

41:21.212 --> 41:23.479
to a hotly debated topic.

41:23.481 --> 41:26.148
MAROD:
It is still very controversial,

41:26.150 --> 41:29.819
but it does help explain
how religion and science

41:29.821 --> 41:31.821
can go hand in hand.

41:31.823 --> 41:34.590
WILDMAN: Today, this tapestry
representing Moses

41:34.592 --> 41:37.626
is on display at the
Virginia Museum of Fine Arts

41:37.628 --> 41:39.028
in Richmond.

41:39.030 --> 41:41.831
It's a reminder of
one man's burning desire

41:41.833 --> 41:44.467
to get to the root
of a mysterious miracle.

41:44.469 --> 41:47.170
♪♪

41:47.172 --> 41:51.574
From a lost labyrinth
to a one-man army,

41:51.576 --> 41:56.646
a pioneering pedestrian
to a cleansing appliance --

41:56.648 --> 41:57.847
I'm Don Wildman,

41:57.849 --> 42:00.183
and these are the
"Mysteries at the Museum."
